# Accessibility requirements

- Use native semantic elements before ARIA or click handlers on generic elements.
- Every interactive control must work with a keyboard and show a visible focus state.
- Give controls an accessible name; associate labels, instructions, and errors with form fields.
- Preserve logical heading order, meaningful link text, and useful image alternatives.
- Do not rely on color alone to communicate state or meaning.
- Respect reduced-motion preferences and avoid unnecessary motion or focus changes.
- Keep touch targets, text wrapping, zoom, and responsive reflow usable.
- Report the manual keyboard and automated accessibility verification performed.
